<https://guia-kg.skai.etsisi.upm.es/resource/595040065/2025-26/evaluation> a ns1:EvaluationSystem ;
    ns1:evaluationDescription """The specific dates of Global Examination and Referred Examination depend on the organization of the School's exam schedule, coordinated by the SOA, and are published in the Annual Teaching Plan (Plan Anual Docente). In case of discrepancy between the information published in this guide and that published in the Annual Teaching Plan, the information published in the Annual Teaching Plan should be taken into account, as it contains the appropriate updates.
Progressive Assessment
* Daily short quiz/equivalent assesable activities on the topic of the day's lesson. Several tests/activities will be held daily in the course. The average mark obtained in these activities accounts for 20 % of the total grade (a test not taken counts as zero for averaging purposes). It is not possible to carry out a second-chance examination for these activities because their aim is to assess the student's contribution during the face-to-face lessons and group work.
* Active participation of students during lectures. Contributing to debates will be taken into account in the assessment. Student participation in debates and discusions accounts for 15% of the total grade. It is not possible to carry out a second chance examination for these activities because their aim is to assess the student's participation in face to face debates.
* Students will work in groups on a topic (proposed by the teachers or by the students themselves and approved by the teachers). They will have to present information on the chosen topic in two formats:
(a) poster, brochure or similar (this task accounts for 30% of the total grade).
(b) oral presentation in class by all members of the group (this presentation accounts for 35% of the total grade).

To pass the course, the student is required to meet all the following conditions:
* Obtain a minimum grade of 3 points (out of 10) in each of the two tasks marked (a) and (b) above.
* Obtain a minimum grade of 5 points (out of 10) in the global mark of the course.
Students who do not meet any of the previous conditions will not be able to obtain a grade higher than 4.0 points (out of 10) in the course.

Global examination
Only those students who have not passed the progressive assessment will have to take the Global Examination. Students will be evaluated based on:
* Daily short quiz/equivalent assesable activities on the topic of the day's lesson. Several tests/activities will be held daily in the course. The average mark obtained in these activities accounts for 20 % of the total grade (a test not taken counts as zero for averaging purposes). It is not possible to carry out a second-chance examination for these activities because their aim is to assess the student's contribution during the face-to-face lessons and group work.
* Active participation of students during lectures. Contributing to debates will be taken into account in the assessment. Student participation in debates and discusions accounts for 15% of the total grade. It is not possible to carry out a second chance examiantion for these activities because their aim is to assess the student's participation in face to face debates.
* Oral presentation (acounts for 30% of the total mark)
* Written test (accounts for 35% of the total mark)
To pass the course, the student is required to meet all the following conditions:
* Obtain a minimum grade of 3 points (out of 10) in each of the two tasks, oral presentation and written test.
* Obtain a minimum grade of 5 points (out of 10) in the global mark of the course.
Students who do not meet any of the previous conditions will not be able to obtain a grade higher than 4.0 points (out of 10) in the course.

Referred examination (July)
* Daily short quiz/equivalent assesable activities on the topic of the day's lesson. Several tests/activities will be held daily in the course. The average mark obtained in these activities accounts for 20 % of the total grade (a test not taken counts as zero for averaging purposes). It is not possible to carry out a make-up exam for these activities because the aim is to assess the student's contribution to the development of the class and face to face group work.
* Active participation of students during lectures, contributing to debates will be taken into account in their assessment. Student participation in debates and discusions account for 15% of the total grade. It is not possible to carry out a make-up exam for these activities because the aim is to assess the student's participation in debates.
* Oral presentation (acounts for 30% of the total mark)
* Written Test (accounts for 35% of the total mark).
To pass the course, the student is required to meet all the following conditions:
* Obtain a minimum grade of 3 points (out of 10) in each of the two tasks, oral presntation and written test.
* Obtain a minimum grade of 5 points (out of 10) in the global mark of the course.
Students who do not meet any of the previous conditions will not be able to obtain a grade higher than 4.0 points (out of 10) in the course."""@es ;
